pullRequest.body:
This defines the typeclass `ZeroLEClass` for `0` being a bottom element (alongside its multiplicative analog `OneLEClass`). This is intended as a mechanism to transfer convenient order theorems about `⊥` to the better behaved algebraic hierarchy (sort of how we did with [`SuccAddOrder`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Order/SuccPred.html#SuccAddOrder) a while back).

The previously most general `bot_eq_zero` lemma on [`CanonicallyOrderedAddCommMonoid`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Order/Monoid/Canonical/Defs.html#CanonicallyOrderedAddCommMonoid) was defined too late to be applicable on `Nat`, `Fin`, and `Multiset`, and was inapplicable to structures such as `Finsupp`, `Ordinal`, or `Nimber`. Now, all this lemma requires is `ZeroLEClass + OrderBot + PartialOrder`, assumptions easy to prove in all cases.

---

Most of this diff just comes from standarizing theorem names and arguments. Notably, `zero_le` now has an implicit argument to match `bot_le` - this seems to be an improvement in 95% of cases.

TODO: unfortunately, `bot_eq_zero` can't be a simp lemma, since submodules use the opposite convention.

I did some easy `CanonicallyOrderedAddCommMonoid` → `ZeroLEClass` generalizations, but there's probably more to be done.

Is `OneLEClass` useful except for multiplicativization of `ZeroLEClass`?

My main motivation here was that using this, you could state some results about `Ordinal` in the wider generality of `SuccAddOrder`, which is useful for my work on ordinal notations. For instance, we currently have [`Order.IsSuccLimit.add_natCast_lt`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Order/SuccPred.html#Order.IsSuccLimit.add_natCast_lt), and if we also had this typeclass we could state more directly that natural a successor limit is larger than any natural number.

In any case, this PR definitely got out of hand. I might retry in the future but without making `bot_eq_zero` into a `simp` lemma. Also, I think making the argument to `zero_le` implicit was a good change, but it ended up taking the majority of this PR, so that too I'll retry elsewhere.
Does this new generality bring us any more concrete types than `Ordinal` + the concrete types already satisfying `CanonicallyOrderedCommMonoid`?

Is `OneLEClass` useful except for multiplicativization of `ZeroLEClass`?
Does this new generality bring us any more concrete types than `Ordinal` + the concrete types already satisfying `CanonicallyOrderedCommMonoid`?

My main motivation here was that using this, you could state some results about `Ordinal` in the wider generality of `SuccAddOrder`, which is useful for my work on ordinal notations. For instance, we currently have [`Order.IsSuccLimit.add_natCast_lt`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Order/SuccPred.html#Order.IsSuccLimit.add_natCast_lt), and if we also had this typeclass we could state more directly that natural a successor limit is larger than any natural number.

In any case, this PR definitely got out of hand. I might retry in the future but without making `bot_eq_zero` into a `simp` lemma. Also, I think making the argument to `zero_le` implicit was a good change, but it ended up taking the majority of this PR, so that too I'll retry elsewhere.
